items.name: Bra v6 fix
items.description:
This is a Bra V6 Fixer.

The Bra V6 is a fantastic model, but getting a good handle on the Brav6 prompts could be a bit of a challenge.

The Bra V6 fixer helps the prompts work a little more as intended, and the LoRAs come out a bit nicer.

Recipe

procedure: almost the same method applied for "chillout NFSW fixer"

  1. try to interpolate input_blocks of Bra V6 to chilloutmix to make LoRA friendly

  2. try to interpolate output_blocks of Bra V6 to dreamshape v8

  3. make a checkpoint

  4. make LoRA using Supermerger (by https://github.com/hako-mikan)/ make Lycoris/Locon version using LyCORIS extract command line tool foundat LyCORIS github project (by https://twitter.com/KBlueleaf)

Please see the following article.

How to make your checkpoint LoRA friendly?

Usage

  • Lora version v1:

    • "<lora:Brav6fix_v1:1>" : LoRA weight ratio could be 0.5~1.5

  • Lycoris/Locon version v1:

    • "<lyco:Brav6fix_locon_v1:0.9>" : Lyco weight ratio could be 0.5~1.5

    • for Lycoris version : download "locon v1" version and copy into stable-diffusion-webui\models\LyCORISsubdir. (it is better to rename downloaded file correctly if the filename is not "Brav6fix_locon_v1.safetensors")

    • from webui 1.5.x(?) you can use <lora:Brav6fix_locon_v1:0.9> without extension. (in this case, you have to copy lyco/locon file into models/LoRA

      • but it seems a bug exists that makes Lycoris not work properly.

License

The same License of Bra V6

items.name: Pixel Art Scenery Style
items.description:
Pixel Art Scenery LoCon

Trained on 200 images of pixel art scenery. I've only tested it on the AnyLoRA checkpoint and i would recommend using it. Use a weight around 0.7 and a CFG Scale of 7 for best results.

Usage

I usually generate an image at 768x512 (or 768x432 for a 16:9 image) and use hires fix at 0.5 denoise, 10 steps and with the R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B upscaler. In addition to that I use the PXL8 extension to downscale the image and reduce the color palette. If I am generating a 768x512 image with hires fix i usually downscale it by 4x to end up with a 384x256 image, I usually put the color palette size at 64. Right now it struggles with character, sometimes it works if they are further away.

Prompting

I would recommend using "scenery, fantasy" mainly. Otherwise just look around on danbooru or other booru sites for tags, some nice ones are "dappled sunlight", "mountainous horizon", "overgrown" etc.

items.name: Bachelor's of Stardew Valley (6 LoRA Pack)
items.description:
Each "version" above is a different character, each character is a separate LoRA.


Beer and coffee keep my motivation up 🍻

The activation tag for each is "[character name] + sdv" aka "alex sdv", "harvey sdv", etc.

Some notes about these LoRA's ↓

- Each LoRA was trained with about 40 images. Because of the original pixelated graphics, there's some debate about specific characteristics such as eye or hair color in cases where it wasn't clear. For example, whether or not Shane and Sebastian have purple hair or if their hair is black and the purple we perceive is a stylistic choice to indicate lighting. Those details are in your hands, specify the color you want to see, they both were tagged and included in the training data.

- In the case of Harvey, I did not tag his eyeglasses or his mustache because during testing I found the character name alone didn't result in a good likeness. You could probably remove them with those tags or similar in the negative prompt.

- In the case of Shane, I think he looks best when you add 'stubble' or 'facial hair' to the prompt.

- And finally, just like every other safetensor LoRA out there, you can open them in a text document and see the complete list of tags they were trained on in the metadata header. Be warned, a bit of lewd data was included in each, Alex had by far the most. This will help you get their typical outfit if you want it though.

If you use this LoRA as part of a mix or host it on a generation service, please mention and link back to this page (especially if you're making money off of it)
